##The other team in the hospital

Wechat, bingdianweekly

Features, China Youth Daily's in depth reporting brand. We believe that news has more than one day of life.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the morning of March 16, a nurse at Wuhan Red Cross Hospital, Ward 1, aspiration medicine, blew gloves into balloons and held the oxygen tube to avoid pressing on the patient. The nurse told the reporter that every time she blew up a balloon, she would write "get well soon" on it to express her good wishes to the patient. China Youth Daily, China Youth Daily, Wang Jiaxing

Zhongqingbao Zhongqingwang reporter, Sun Qingling, Wang Xinxin

In Ward 23 of the East Ward of the People's Hospital of Wuhan University, Yang Xiufang is probably the medical staff who talks most to patients.

Her voice was soft and slow. In the ward, wrapped in a thick layer of three-level protection, her voice was a little higher than usual, the ups and downs of sound waves landing on the body or into the ears, a patient described as "like the spring breeze blowing" , some recognize her as she speaks the first words.

Yang Xiufang's words are not only the transmission of information, can also be said to be a pair of antiviral "medicine. ". She is from the Mental Health Center of Hwaseo Hospital in Sichuan University. She arrived in Wuhan on February 7. She is also the first psychological consultant from the medical team from Sichuan Province to support Wuhan.

A week later, two other psychologists with the seventh and eighth batches of Sichuan medical team arrived in Wuhan. Half a month later, Sichuan Province sent a team of 50 psychological consultants, psychiatrists, the tenth batch of medical teams. At present, 415 mental health professionals have been dispatched to Hubei by the National Health Commission to provide professional psychological consultation and crisis intervention services for patients and medical personnel.

They are called "psychological warfare team" , not to win over, but to accompany. In the words of team member Ye Jialu, is to accompany the new pneumonia patients, first-line medical staff to carry out this difficult period.

Catharsis. I don't know where to start

Chen Wen (pseudonym) , who lives in Ward 23 of the People's Hospital of Wuhan University, compared with some patients who are too scared to eat, can be regarded as a kind of patients who make nurses feel more comfortable, follow the doctor's orders, injection, infusion, not fierce and not decadent.

But the third night, she suddenly because of a late delivery of rice burst into tears, the medical staff, patients startled. A long backlog of grievances, pain, fear, and even despair, poured out.

Chen Wen, who is in his 50s, is still unclear how he got the new pneumonia. When she was admitted to the hospital, she told herself she would be treated with peace of mind, but she did not know why. She asked herself a series of questions, asking why, what she wanted to vent, and to whom and where.

Chen Wen's ward has 3 patients, basically no communication, "everyone is very depressed, afraid, do not speak" , sleep lights do not dare to turn off.

The horror of the new coronavirus is not only in its destruction of the body, but also in its forced isolation of people. "It can create a sense of deprivation and insecurity, and even if you can talk by phone or video, the lack of physical contact can still block the natural flow of some emotions, " said Li Shuiying, a psychologist with the 10th medical team in Sichuan Province who was in contact with a patient, her 7-year-old son, who is in isolation, calls her every hour or so, day and night, "because the child's sense of security is not satisfied. ".

Yang Xiufang's ward currently has 24 patients, and most of them are middle-aged and elderly. Some use "old mobile phones, " others don't use Wechat, and it's not realistic to talk and make calls for long periods of time -- a place where online psychological assistance is hard to reach.

Some old people will keep ringing the bell to call the medical staff, the medical staff moves slightly slower, the old people will lose their temper; some patients who have been rescued Python say "don't want to live" after waking up, because "feel neglected" ; There are also patients wearing oxygen masks laboriously on the paper to write 4 words "will I die" , staring at Yang Xiufang can give an answer.

There were a few more voices in the room

Every day, Yang Xiufang completed the psychological screening of new patients admitted to hospital, will first focus on several patients with poor psychological state. She stood talking to them, sometimes for three or four hours at a time, till she could hardly breathe.

Chen Wen likes to listen to Yang Xiufang. The same words of encouragement, but Yang Xiufang to ward everyone said different, and Chen Wen feel words to his heart, "every word is slowly flowing into the heart, not a pot of water pour to you. ". But sometimes, Yang Xiufang just quietly listening, holding each other's hand, or holding each other's shoulder, "let them feel someone in, their own not so lonely. ".

Chen Wen did not know how to use language to describe the feeling of holding Yang Xiufang's hand, only felt that he was "almost ready to cry" , but could not cry. Because "a warm current drilling into the heart, " as if they re-connected with the world.

Chen Wen used "careful" "warm-hearted" "patient" to describe other medical staff, and "intimate" to describe Yang Xiufang. "She seems to understand my worries and fears. ".

Psychologists seem to have a special "magic" that can read people. "they tend to be very empathetic, and although they can't fully empathize, they are sensitive to the feelings of their patients, " Ms. Yip said, sometimes just listening to a stranger's voice and trying to get inside someone's head, to feel what they feel, to resonate with their emotions. Sometimes it can take me a while to digest the grief that comes from a visit after the session is over.

Not all psychologists are strong at heart, but they are good at detecting mood swings. They help the patient to share and digest the complicated emotions, accompany each other through the fog to the beautiful scenery, soul-stirring, but seemingly UNMOVING.

The daily counseling continues. Recently, a patient who had lost her husband told her, "I had dinner and washed the dishes, so I thought I'd wait for foliage to call me. " They still don't talk about the dead or avoid talking about them, even the talk was more of quiet than grief, Ms. Yip wrote in her work diary. "This is a silent mourning leading to a hopeful tomorrow. ".

If Yang Xiufang does not appear in the ward, Chen Wen and the patients will start to say, "why isn't Yang coming yet? " "It feels like a long time has not come. " "How do you feel now? " ... Slowly, several voices began to appear in the ward, talking, laughing, and even Chen Wen singing "I and my motherland. ". "It was Dr. Yang's presence that woke this place up, " she said.

Now that Chen has been released from the hospital and transferred to isolation, he is one step closer to going home. She says she still misses Yang Xiufang. She had never seen Yang Xiufang without protective clothing, but she remembered her voice and her eyes.

Come closer. Come closer

Yang Xiufang followed her medical team into the ward to work directly. In contrast to her, Jiang Lijun, a psychologist and secretary of the 10th medical team from Sichuan who supported Wuhan, spent most of her first week in Wuhan "waiting for patients. ".

According to the arrangement, the 50 psychologists in Jiang's medical team were divided into 10 groups, five of whom were paired up with a hospital / shelter, and the medical staff were their primary service group.

Qiu Changjian, head of the mental health team of the Sichuan Medical Team Supporting Wuhan, observed that health care workers were more likely to keep emotions in their hearts than patients. Some medical staff in the call advisory just say "very tired AH" , immediately put it back; some medical staff is very tired, but still not under the "line of fire" , because they feel that they are to support, can not fall.

To understand and help them, you have to be close to them, closer.

Jiang Lijun Group first contact the hospital / shelter in the various medical teams, issued psychological scale "to find out" the psychological status of medical staff. Some hospital leaders or team leaders to cooperate, some requests to this psychological scale of some of the problems, some directly rejected them.

Jiang Lijun came up with a plan, she asked in advance the docking medical team shift time, seize the opportunity and rest of the medical staff to chat. The most important part of counseling and intervention is the principle of voluntariness, which is basically telling them, "I'm here if you need me. ".

Some of the hotel lobbies where medical teams were stationed became Jiang Lijun's "office" ; in some places there were no seats, so she brought her own stool..

Some of Jiang Lijun's teammates set up a simple "psychological consulting room" in the medical staff's station and tried to make friends with the medical staff. "When you are in front of him, the psychological distance between you is different, " said Zhang Bo, a psychologist with the 10th medical team in Sichuan Province.

Jiang Lijun statistics, in the first half of the team received more than 1,000 consultations, medical staff less than patients, accounting for about 40% .

According to Zhang Bo, the main cause of psychological problems among health care workers is work stress, "The medical field is like a mountain, and now all the departments have become as one department —— The smoking department -- and those from other departments, such as the Oral Department and the Radiology Department, have to get used to it, adding to the stress of the job. ".

Qiu Changjian said that under high-intensity and high-intensity Stress State, the real emotional or psychological problems of the medical staff will be suppressed to a certain extent, and will be manifested through sleep or physical reactions, such as dizziness, head distension and slow reaction, "In this state, it is Ok to fight hard battles, but not for a long time. ".

That's what shrinks are for.

At times, Jiang and her teammates set to work directly in the hotel lobby, looking for a quiet, secluded spot. These online or offline, mobile or fixed "counseling rooms, " like a "shelter" outside the ward, where some medical staff to remove the crown, can cry, can also shout, to remove anxiety, vulnerability and insecurity.

By the time they got out, "some of their eyes had regained some of their sparkle, " and some had become friends with their therapist.

At the moment, Jiang Lijun said she had also been "honorably laid off" because the medical team she had docked with had been evacuated from Wuhan, and "many psychological problems are periodic and will gradually recover after their recuperation. Wuhan's special experience will enrich their life experience, and some will even become an opportunity for their growth. ".
